Markov chain Monte Carlo with the Integrated Nested Laplace Approximation

Martin Outzen Berild

September 03, 2019

Bayesian Lasso

Theory

Lasso regression performs both coefficient estimates and feature selection at the same time. The estimation is done by the equation

\[ \mathrm{minimize} \sum\limits_{i=1}^n\left(y_i - \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^p\beta_jx_{ij}\right)^2 + \lambda \sum\limits_{j=1}^p|\beta_j|, \] where \(y_i\) is the response and \(x_ij\). There are \(n\) observations and \(p\) covariates. The penality term \(\lambda\) is found with the minimization and cross-validation and is set to be \(\lambda = 0.73\). The coefficients have Laplace priors, which is defined as \[ \pi(\beta) = \frac{1}{2\sigma} \mathrm{exp}\left(-\frac{|\beta - \mu|}{\sigma} \right), x \in \mathbb{R}. \]

\(\mu = 0\) and \(\sigma = 1/\tau = 1/0.73\) are location and scale, and are assumed to be independent a priori s.t. the prior is given by the product of five Laplace distributions.

The response will be modelled by \[ \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{X}\mathbf{\beta} + \mathbf{\epsilon},\enspace \mathbf{\epsilon} \sim \mathcal{N}_n(\mathbf{0},\frac{1}{\tau}\mathbf{I_n}), \] which implies that \(\mathbf{y} \sim \mathcal{N}_n(\mathbf{x}\mathbf{\beta},\frac{1}{\tau}\mathbf{I_n}))\). We will also assume that \(\mathbf{\beta}\) and \(\tau\) are independent a prior, meaning \(\pi(\mathbf{\beta},\tau) = \pi(\mathbf{\beta})\pi(\tau)\). Further the coefficient \(\mathbf{\beta}\) will have a Gaussian proposal distribution given by

\[ \mathbf{\beta}^* \sim q(\beta^*\, | \, \beta, \mathbf{y}, \tau) = \mathcal{N}_p\left(\mathbf{0},(4\cdot\mathbf{X}^T\mathbf{X})^{-1}\right), \]

This might be wrong! mean of previous \(\beta\). Currently being tested

and the prior for \(\tau\) is given by \[ \tau \sim \mathrm{Gamma}\left(1, 5\mathrm{e}-0.5\right). \]

The posterior distribution is given by \[ \pi(\beta,\tau \, | \, \mathbf{y}) \propto \pi(\mathbf{y}|\beta,\tau)\pi(\beta)\pi(\tau), \] thereby yielding the posterior marginal distributions \[ \pi(\beta\, | \, \mathbf{y},\tau) \propto \pi(\mathbf{y}|\beta,\tau)\pi(\beta) \] and

\[ \begin{align} \pi(\tau\, | \, \mathbf{y},\beta) & \propto \pi(\mathbf{y}|\beta,\tau)\pi(\tau) \\ & \propto \tau^{\phi - 1}\mathrm{e}^{-\tau/\theta}\tau^{1/2}\exp\left\{\frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)^T\tau\mathbf{I}_n(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)\right\} \\ & = \tau^{\phi + \frac{1}{2} - 1} \exp\left\{-\tau(\frac{1}{\theta} + \frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)^T(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)) \right\} \\ & \propto \mathrm{Gamma}\left\{\phi + \frac{1}{2}, \left(\frac{1}{\theta} + \frac{1}{2}(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)^T(\mathbf{y}-\mathbf{X}\beta)\right) ^{-1} \right\}. \end{align} \] We can sample from the conditional marginal of \(\tau\), but there are no known distribution for the conditional marginal of \(\beta\). Therefore we must find posterior marginals of \(\beta\) by a Metropolitan-Hastings step, with block update on the model parameters.

Method

prior.beta <- function(x, mu = 0, lambda = 1/0.73, log = TRUE) {
  res = sum(log(ddoublex(x, mu = mu, lambda = lambda)))
  
  if(!log) { res = exp(res) }
  
  return(res)
}
dq.beta <- function(x, y, sigma = stdev.samp, log =TRUE) {
  dmvnorm(y, mean = x, sigma = sigma, log = log)
}
rq.beta <- function(x, sigma = stdev.samp) {
  as.vector(rmvnorm(1, mean = x, sigma = sigma))
}

McMC

Using the Markov chain Monte Carlo we need to draw samples from the conditional marginal of \(\tau\). This is done by the function r.tau().

r.tau <- function(data, beta){
  shape = 1.5
  scale = 1/(1/(5*10^(-5)) + t(data$y - data$x%*%beta)%*%(data$y - data$x%*%beta))
  rgamma(1, shape = shape, scale = scale)
}

From the markov assumption and the Metropolis choice the acceptance probability is given by

\[ \alpha = \min\left\{1, \frac{\pi(\mathbf{y}\, | \, \beta^*,\tau)\pi(\beta^*)q(\beta\, | \, \beta^*)}{\pi(\mathbf{y}\, | \, \beta,\tau)\pi(\beta)q(\beta^*\, | \, \beta)}\right\} \]

McMC with INLA

The Laplace prior is not available in R-INLA, but by fixating the values of \(\beta\), and conditioning on them, the model can be fitted. This means that we draw from the same proposal distribution to get samples of \(\beta\). Then we fit the model with R-INLA, to get the conditional marginal likelihood \(\pi(\mathbf{y}\, | \, \beta)\), and the approximation of the conditional marginal distribution \(\pi(\tau\, | \, \mathbf{y},\beta)\). The posterior marginal \(\pi(\tau\, | \, \mathbf{y})\) is then found by Bayesian model averaging. The acceptance probability is now given by the equation \[ \alpha = \min\left\{1,\frac{\pi(\mathbf{y}\, | \, \beta^*)\pi(\beta^*)q(\beta\, | \, \beta^*)}{\mathbf{y}\, | \, \beta)\pi(\beta)q(\beta^*\, | \, \beta)}\right\} \]
